# Run

Shortcut-drive the current lifecycle stage until it surfaces a next skill,
blocker, or done-ready outcome.

## Invocation
```bash
slipway run --json
slipway run --resume --json
```

## Contract
- `run` is an auto-driver shortcut. The primary stage commands are `intake`,
  `plan`, `implement`, `review`, and `done`.
- JSON output includes `delegated_to` so hosts can see which primary stage
  command `run` invoked for the current state.
- `run --resume` resumes governed execution from the latest incomplete wave.
- If resumable execution exists, plain `run` is rejected and `--resume` is required.
- `run` reuses the same `next --json` contract for the returned next-skill / blocker surface.
- `advanced` reports the mutation performed by this invocation; `blockers` reports the current stop condition after that mutation. A successful advance can still return error-severity blockers for the next required skill.
- Branch on `confirmation_requirement.next_action_kind` and run `confirmation_requirement.next_command` when present (`next_action` is human prose, not a contract to parse).
- Under auto (`execution.auto` or `slipway run --auto`), the run loop may continue only routine `run_slipway_run_to_advance` command boundaries after a successful advance. Pending workflow-preset confirmation is auto-confirmed upgrade-only.
- Skill handoffs and review batches still stop the run loop for host work. Non-sensitive/non-guardrail handoffs may be reported by `next --json` as `evidence_continuation` instead of `hard_stop`, but the host still must run the skill or review batch and record evidence.
- Auto never crosses sensitive/guardrail confirmations, `security-review` boundaries, the intake Approved Summary, done finalization, or evidence gates.
- Treat default JSON as the action contract. Use `slipway run --json --diagnostics` only for full readiness fields.
- If governance control details are needed, run `slipway health --governance --json --change <slug>`.
- Do not expect inline policy-pack prose in default JSON; read policy-pack content only by path from diagnostics or config.

## When To Use
- You want Slipway to keep advancing / validating until the workflow surfaces the next skill or another stop condition.
- You are resuming wave execution after a prior interruption.

## Pause Conditions
- A next skill is surfaced.
- Blockers are present.
- The change is done-ready or done.

## Session Continuity (SHOULD)
Slipway does not measure your context during a long `run`; the timing is yours. If
your host judges its own context is running low, preserve continuity before you
compact or start a fresh session: pipe a narrative into `slipway handoff write`
(e.g. `printf '## Current Position\n...' | slipway handoff write`). Resolve
`<slug>` from fresh `slipway status --json` / `slipway next --json`, not from the
handoff body. The handoff is advisory only; it does not replace
`slipway status --json`, `slipway next --json`, lifecycle gates, freshness, or
evidence checks.

## Fresh Reviewer Pause Rule
When `run` reaches a selected S3 peer reviewer, stop and hand off to a fresh reviewer agent.
Follow `next_skill.selected_review_skills` from the current output. The
baseline selected peer set is `spec-compliance-review` and
`independent-review`; it adds `code-quality-review`
when selected by the workflow profile and `security-review` when selected by
policy. Do not let the same long-running execution context review its own prior
implementation work. `ship-verification` is the last terminal step after the
selected peer set, not a selected S3 peer.

## Fresh Context Boundary Rule (HARD RULE)
Use a fresh subagent for governed review handoffs, especially selected S3 peer
reviewers. A plain operator confirmation to run an advancing command after
already-recorded evidence does not by itself require spawning a subagent; the
current host may run that lifecycle transition and then stop at any review
batch, blocker, or next-skill handoff. Do not let the same implementation
context perform its own selected S3 peer review evidence.

## Failure Handling
1. On any command/runtime error, stop and show the error details.
2. On evidence validation failure, stop and require targeted remediation.
3. If three consecutive skills fail, exit the loop and require manual intervention before retrying.

## Flags
- `--resume`: continue resumable execution from the latest incomplete wave
- `--json`: JSON output
- `--change <slug>`: target a specific active change
- `--diagnostics`: include governance/readiness diagnostic fields
- `--auto`/`--no-auto`: override `execution.auto` for this run; auto continues only routine `run_slipway_run_to_advance` command boundaries, never skill/review handoffs, `security-review` boundaries, sensitive confirmations, or evidence gates
